 {"id":"bd-11w","title":"Implement output_schema for tool macros","description":"# Implement output_schema for Tool Macros

## Background
Python FastMCP supports specifying an output schema for tools, enabling clients to understand the structure of tool results. This improves IDE support, validation, and documentation.

## Requirements

### Macro Attribute
```rust
#[tool(output_schema = json!({
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
        "result": { "type": "string" },
        "count": { "type": "integer" }
    }
}))]
async fn analyze(text: String) -> AnalysisResult {
    // ...
}

// Or using a type that implements JsonSchema
#[tool(output_schema = AnalysisResult)]
async fn analyze_typed(text: String) -> AnalysisResult {
    // ...
}
```

### Protocol Extension
```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct Tool {
    pub name: String,
    pub description: Option<String>,
    #[serde(rename = "inputSchema")]
    pub input_schema: Value,
    /// Schema describing the tool's output structure
    #[serde(rename = "outputSchema", skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]
    pub output_schema: Option<Value>,
    // ... other fields
}
```

### Handler Trait Extension
```rust
pub trait ToolHandler: Send + Sync {
    fn name(&self) -> &str;
    fn description(&self) -> Option<&str> { None }
    fn input_schema(&self) -> Value;

    /// Output schema for tool results
    fn output_schema(&self) -> Option<Value> { None }

    async fn call(&self, ctx: &McpContext, args: Value) -> McpResult<CallToolResult>;
}
```

## Files to Modify
- crates/fastmcp-protocol/src/types.rs
- crates/fastmcp-server/src/handler.rs
- crates/fastmcp-macros/src/tool.rs

## User Experience Considerations
- Support both inline JSON schema and type reference
- Validate output against schema in debug mode
- Generate schema from return type when possible (schemars)

---

## Comprehensive Testing Requirements

### Unit Tests

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod output_schema_tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_tool_serializes_with_output_schema() {
        let tool = Tool {
            name: "analyze".into(),
            output_schema: Some(json!({
                "type": "object",
                "properties": { "result": { "type": "string" } }
            })),
            ..Default::default()
        };

        let json = serde_json::to_string(&tool).unwrap();
        assert!(json.contains("outputSchema"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_tool_serializes_without_output_schema() {
        let tool = Tool {
            name: "simple".into(),
            output_schema: None,
            ..Default::default()
        };

        let json = serde_json::to_string(&tool).unwrap();
        assert!(!json.contains("outputSchema"));
    }

    #[test]
    fn test_handler_default_output_schema_none() {
        struct SimpleHandler;
        impl ToolHandler for SimpleHandler {
            fn name(&self) -> &str { "simple" }
            fn input_schema(&self) -> Value { json!({}) }
            async fn call(&self, _: &McpContext, _: Value) -> McpResult<CallToolResult> {
                unimplemented!()
            }
        }

        assert!(SimpleHandler.output_schema().is_none());
    }
}
```

### Macro Tests

```rust
#[test]
fn test_macro_inline_output_schema() {
    #[tool(output_schema = json!({"type": "string"}))]
    async fn simple_output() -> String {
        "result".into()
    }

    let handler = simple_output::handler();
    assert!(handler.output_schema().is_some());
}

#[test]
fn test_macro_type_derived_schema() {
    #[derive(Serialize, JsonSchema)]
    struct Output { value: i32 }

    #[tool(output_schema = Output)]
    async fn typed_output() -> Output {
        Output { value: 42 }
    }

    let handler = typed_output::handler();
    let schema = handler.output_schema().unwrap();
    assert!(schema["properties"]["value"]["type"] == "integer");
}
```

### Integration Tests

